<paper id="1588769217"><title>Adaptively-Secure Optimal-Resilience Proactive RSA</title><year>1999</year><authors><author org="CertCo" id="2956395300">Yair Frankel</author><author org="Bell-Labs" id="2167787271">Philip D. MacKenzie</author><author org="CertCo" id="2097786798">Moti Yung</author></authors><n_citation>35</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1493614564</reference><reference>1502416796</reference><reference>1515956543</reference><reference>1540442590</reference><reference>1546996295</reference><reference>1599603597</reference><reference>1607430658</reference><reference>1631229389</reference><reference>1646354800</reference><reference>1885156594</reference><reference>1928188623</reference><reference>1967263393</reference><reference>1983762057</reference><reference>2036788199</reference><reference>2096024255</reference><reference>2096430557</reference><reference>2114611273</reference><reference>2134149606</reference><reference>2147270806</reference><reference>2168970529</reference><reference>2230112138</reference><reference>2612546616</reference><reference>2912577494</reference><reference>2913982177</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-48000-6_15</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.49907">Secret sharing</keyword><keyword weight="0.43537">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45555">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.56048">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.46217">Information protection policy</keyword><keyword weight="0.4811">Encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.51697">Proactive maintenance</keyword><keyword weight="0.44695">Systems management</keyword><keyword weight="0.5696">Public-key cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.49296">Scalability</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer Berlin Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>When attacking a distributed protocol, an adaptive adversary may determine its actions (e.g., which parties to corrupt), at any time, based on its entire view of the protocol including the entire communication history. In this paper we are concerned with proactive RSA protocols, i.e., robust distributed RSA protocols that rerandomize key shares at certain intervals to reduce the threat of long-term attacks. Here we design the first proactive RSA system that is secure against an adaptive adversaries. The system achieves “optimal-resilience” and “secure space scalability” (namely O(1) keys per user).</abstract></paper>